Story tier list?
Making It by Mattariel has to be my number one. I love fantasy, and I don't think I've ever been so jealous of someone else's creativity. It's a masterpiece.
LoF, WKW, HYSTN, Yagato Mountain, those are all upper eschelon classics. I agree with you completely that they belong on any 'best of' list. Acid Rain has moments of iffy quality, and I don't like the more recent continuations of it, but that piece also means a lot to me.
Today's Demons, Nights of Firefall, Hair of the Dog and HEL Jumper are also great stories that belong in that discussion.
Silver Lining is getting a rework that I am very excited for, too, although I want to wait until more of that story is finished before I dive back in.
Call of the Waifur, FFI, and Motorknight were all great stories robbed of their conclusions, abandoned before completion. They will be missed.
There are a couple of stories I would challenge you on. I've already given my thoughts on HATSSSSS and Mechanized in the past, but I can at least see the appeal in those two stories even if for me their issues outweigh my enjoyment. Mechanized understands character development and has a great dynamic between its leads, and for the first stretch of HATSSSSS, the slice of life chapters with Missy are very endearing.
Monster in the Closet is shit story with awful prose and inert characters. And while I acknowledge that it's difficult to divorce your art from your politics, few stories here have handled their agenda in such a tactless piss-poor manner.

Anonymous Mon 25 Apr 2022 15:50:51 No.47209182 Report

>>47208476
That might be part of it. Part of it, I think, is that nerd culture has always been consciously contrarian, motivated by a desire to show how different we are from "the normies," ever since nerds emerged as a distinct subculture fifty years ago. See a grimdark anime about the end of the world? Write fanfiction where you put the characters in a sitcom! Hear about a cute sugary kids' property? Watch it, then write a crossover fic with Fallout so that all the world can see the adorable characters dying of radiation sickness!

It isn't just fanfic. Nerd culture always takes the opposite tack from general popculture. 1970s-80s popculture hit you over the head with environmental collapse and nuclear apocalypse, zombie movies and Mad Max. Nerds fled to Tolkien and Dungeons & Dragons, for magical high-fantasy escapism. After the collapse of the USSR, 1990s popular culture had a much more optimistic tone. Nerds immediately embraced grimderp darker-n-edgier cape comic reboots, Japanese cartoons about neurotic and morally ambiguous people caught up in giant robot Ragnarok, and tryhard pen-and-paper RPGs about being a werewolf or vampire in a dying world. Since 9/11 popular culture has gotten really pessimistic again--as an aside, whenever vampires and the concept of zombie apocalypse become big pop-culture phenomena, it means the normies are scared shitless and either want to be beautiful ageless undead or kill the mindless zombies who are destroying the world, these are fantasies that resonate with people who are terrified of the future and terrified the world is about to end. Nerds dropped Evangelion in favor of My Little Pony, cheerful "steampunk" alternate-universe Victorian adventures, and slice-of-life anime about silly teenage girls. If anything the greentext generals in /mlp/ run counter to that, because they consciously embrace the silly.

Here. Have a horse anthro girl. Isn't she pretty?
